\par \'93I've always prided myself on seeing things the way they truly are,\'94 Thufir Hawat said. \'93That's the curse of being a Mentat. You can't stop analyzing your data.\'94
\par The leathered old face appeared composed in the predawn dimness as he spoke. His sapho-stained lips were drawn into a straight line with radial creases spreading upward.
\par A robed man squatted silently on sand across from Hawat, apparently unmoved by the words.
\par The two crouched beneath a rock overhang that looked down on a wide, shallow 
sink. Dawn was spreading over the shattered outline of cliffs across the basin, touching everything with pink. It was cold under the overhang, a dry and penetrating chill left over from the night. There had been a warm wind just before dawn, but now it wa
s cold. Hawat could hear teeth chattering behind him among the few troopers remaining in his force.
\par The man squatting across from Hawat was a Fremen who had come across the sink in the first light of false dawn, skittering over the sand, blending into the dunes, his movements barely discernible.
\par The Fremen extended a finger to the sand between them, drew a figure there. It looked like a bowl with an arrow spilling out of it. \'93There are many Harkonnen patrols,\'94 he said. He lifted his finger, pointed upward ac
ross the cliffs that Hawat and his men had descended.
\par Hawat nodded. 
\par Many patrols. Yes.
\par But still he did not know what this Fremen wanted and this rankled. Mentat training was supposed to give a man the power to see motives.
\par This had been the worst night of Hawat's life. He had been at Tsimpo, a garrison village, buffer outpost for the former capital city, Carthag, when the reports of attack began arriving. At first, he'd thought: It's a raid. The Harkonnens are testing.  

\par But report followed report\endash faster and faster. 
\par Two legions landed at Carthag.
\par Five legions\endash fifty brigades! \endash attacking the Duke's main base at Arrakeen.
\par A legion at Arsunt.
\par Two battle groups at Splintered Rock.
\par Then the reports became more detailed\endash there were Imperial Sardaukar among the attackers\endash possibly two legions of them. And it became clear that the invaders knew precisely which weight of arms to send where. Precisely! Superb Intelligence.

\par Hawat's shocked fury had mounted until it threatened the smooth functioning of his Mentat capabilities. The size of the attack struck his mind like a physical blow.
\par Now, hiding beneath a bit of desert rock, he nodded to himself, pulled his torn and slashed tunic around him as though warding off the cold shadows.
\par The size of the attack.
\par He had always e
xpected their enemy to hire an occasional lighter from the Guild for probing raids. That was an ordinary enough gambit in this kind of House-to-House warfare. Lighters landed and took off on Arrakis regularly to transport the spice for House Atreides. Haw
at had taken precautions against random raids by false spice lighters. For a full attack they'd expected no more than ten brigades.
\par But there were more than two thousand ships down on Arrakis at the last count\endash not just lighters, but frigates, scouts, monitors, crushers, troop-carriers, dump-boxes\'85 
\par More than a hundred brigades\endash ten legions!
\par The entire spice income of Arrakis for fifty years might just cover the cost of such a venture. 
\par It might.
\par I underestimated what the Baron was willing to spend in attacking us, Hawat thought. I failed my Duke. 
\par Then there was the matter of the traitor.
\par I will live long enough to see her strangled! he thought. I should've killed that Bene Gesserit witch when I had the chance. There was no doubt in his mind who had betrayed them\endash the Lady Jessica. She fitted all the facts available.
\par \'93Your man Gurney Halleck and part of his force are safe with our smuggler friends,\'94 the Fremen said. 
\par \'93Good.\'94 
\par So Gurney will get off this hell planet. We \lquote re not all gone.
\par Hawat glanced back at the
 huddle of his men. He had started the night just past with three hundred of his finest. Of those, an even twenty remained and half of them were wounded. Some of them slept now, standing up, leaning against the rock, sprawled on the sand beneath the rock.
 Their last \lquote 
thopter, the one they'd been using as a ground-effect machine to carry their wounded, had given out just before dawn. They had cut it up with lasguns and hidden the pieces, then worked their way down into this hiding place at the edge of the basin.
\par Hawat had only a rough idea of their location\endash some two hundred kilometers southeast of Arrakeen. The main traveled ways between the Shield Wall sietch communities were somewhere south of them.
\par The Fremen across from Hawat threw back his hood and still
suit cap to reveal sandy hair and beard. The hair was combed straight back from a high, thin forehead. He had the unreadable total blue eyes of the spice diet. Beard and mustache were stained at one side of the mouth, his hair matted there by pressure of 
the looping catchtube from his nose plugs.
\par The man removed his plugs, readjusted them. He rubbed at a scar beside his nose.
\par \'93If you cross the sink here this night,\'94 the Fremen said, \'93you must not use shields. There is a break in the wall\'85 \'94 He turned on his heels, pointed south. \'93\'85 there, and it is open sand down to the erg. Shields will attract a\'85 \'94
 He hesitated. \'93\'85 worm. They don't often come in here, but a shield will bring one every time.\'94 
\par He said worm, Hawat thought. He was going to say something else. What? And what does he want of us? 
\par Hawat sighed.
\par He could not recall ever before being this tired. It was a muscle weariness that energy pills were unable to ease. 
\par Those damnable Sardaukar!
\par With a self-accusing bitterness, he faced the thought of the so
ldier-fanatics and the Imperial treachery they represented. His own Mentat assessment of the data told him how little chance he had ever to present evidence of this treachery before the High Council of the Landsraad where justice might be done.
\par \'93Do you wish to go to the smugglers?\'94 the Fremen asked. 
\par \'93Is it possible?\'94 
\par \'93The way is long.\'94 
\par \'93Fremen don't like to say no,\'94 Idaho had told him once.
\par Hawat said: \'93You haven't yet told me whether your people can help my wounded.\'94 
\par \'93They are wounded.\'94 
\par The same damned answer every time!
\par \'93We know they're wounded!\'94 Hawat snapped. \'93That's not the\endash \'94
\par \'93Peace, friend,\'94 the Fremen cautioned. \'93What do your wounded say? Are there those among them who can see the water need of your tribe?\'94 
\par \'93We haven't talked about water,\'94 Hawat said. \'93We\endash \'94 
\par \'93I can understand your reluctance,\'94 the Fremen said. \'93They are your friends, your tribesmen. Do you have water?\'94 
